{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dac95690-ec2e-434c-9068-730cdc02c460","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** – downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with the current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** – re-installs the *same* versions already recorded; it fixes corrupted or missing files but won't pull newer packages.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, check `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` (or `maui-windows`, `maui-ios`, etc.) workloads are present and up-to-date.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3fa52492-1d51-461a-9c72-840be8c7153e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to look at any files.","outputTokens":230,"requestId":"0811:348511:A2EC70:BC2D58:69F2A76C"},"id":"4af7ac00-a444-43ba-be24-b4e8928f79c9","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:50:58.871Z","parentId":"8b89bad9-70e2-494b-a8e0-699a5683c1f3"}
